  "prompt": "How many layers should you wear on cold winter days?",
  "response": "The number of layers you should wear on cold winter days can vary depending on several factors, including the temperature, your activity level, and individual comfort. However, a general guideline is to follow the \"three-layer rule\":\n\n1. **Base Layer**: This layer is worn next to your skin and is designed to wick moisture away from your body. Look for materials like merino wool, synthetic fibers, or moisture-wicking fabrics.\n\n2. **Insulating Layer**: The second layer provides insulation to retain body heat. Fleece, down, or synthetic insulation are good choices. You can adjust the thickness based on how cold it is.\n\n3. **Outer Layer**: The outer layer protects you from wind, rain, and snow. It should be waterproof and breathable, such as a windbreaker or a waterproof jacket.\n\nDepending on the severity of the cold and your activity, you can add extra layers such as additional insulation or thicker socks, gloves, and hats. Always consider layering versatility, allowing you to add or remove layers based on changes in temperature or activity level.",
